{"title_page": "J. Mark Spalding", "text_new": "{{Other people|Mark Spalding}}\n\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type              = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix  = [[Excellency|His Excellency]], [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name              = J. Mark Spalding\n| honorific-suffix  = [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]], [[Licentiate of Canon Law|J.C.L.]]\n| title             = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Bishop of Nashville]]\n| image             = J. Mark Spalding 2019.png\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Spalding in 2019\n| archdiocese       = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville|Louisville]]\n| diocese           = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Nashville]]\n| appointed         = November 21, 2017\n| enthroned         = February 2 ([[Candlemas]]), 2018\n| retired           =\n| predecessor       = [[David Choby]]\n| successor         = \n| other_post        = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination        = August 3, 1991\n| ordained_by       = [[Thomas C. Kelly]], [[Dominican Order|O.P]]\n| consecration      = February 2 (Candlemas), 2018\n| consecrated_by    = [[Joseph Edward Kurtz]], [[Charles C. Thompson]], and [[William Medley]]<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram>{{cite book | last= | first= | authorlink= | title=Mass of the Episcopal Ordination and Installation of His Excellency, The Most Reverend J. Mark Spalding, D.D., J.C.L. as the Twelfth Bishop of Nashville (program) | publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville]] | series= | volume= | edition= | date= | location= | pages=36 | language=English | url= | doi= | id= | isbn= | mr= | zbl= | jfm=}}</ref>\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name        =  Joseph Mark Spalding<!---------- Archbishop Kurtz mistakenly identified him as Joseph Mark Spalding in the Mass of his episcopal ordination and installment ---------->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1965|01|13}} \n| birth_place       = [[Lebanon, Kentucky]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| buried            = \n| nationality       = {{flag|USA|name=American}}\n| religion          = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence         = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| parents           = Joseph Lawrence and Mary Aileen (nee Thompson) Spalding<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n| spouse            = \n| occupation        = \n| profession        = \n| previous_post     = [[Vicar general|Vicar General]] of Louisville (2011-2018)<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><br />Pastor of Holy Trinity Church ([[Louisville, Kentucky]]; 2011-2018)<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><br />Pastor of Holy Name Church (2016-2018)<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n| alma_mater        = [[Saint Meinrad Seminary and School of Theology]]<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><br />\"Catholic University of Louvain\"<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /> (it is not clear whether this refers to [[KU Leuven]] or [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]])\n| motto             = GOD HAS LIFTED UP THE LOWLY (from [[Magnificat#Roman Catholic translation|Luke 1:52]])<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n| coat_of_arms      = Coat of arms of J. Mark Spalding.svg\n}}\n\n{{Infobox bishopstyles  \n| name=  J. Mark Spalding\n| dipstyle=  \n*[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n*[[The Most Reverend]]    \n| offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] \n| relstyle=[[Bishop]] \n| image = Coat of arms of J. Mark Spalding.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Mark Spalding''',<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/nash1.htm#61700 | title=Diocese of Nashville USA | website=GCatholic.org | accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]],<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /> [[Licentiate of Canon Law|J.C.L.]] (born January 13, 1965 in [[Lebanon, Kentucky]]) is an [[United States|American]] priest and [[bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He is the twelfth [[bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Diocese of Nashville]].<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n\n==Biography==\nSpalding was born in Lebanon, Kentucky and grew up on the family farm in [[Washington County, Kentucky|Washington County]]. His family has roots in the earliest [[Bardstown, Kentucky#History|Catholic presence in the United States west of the Appalachian Mountains]];<ref>[https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/religion/2018/02/01/nashville-new-bishop-j-mark-spalding/1018787001/ Meyer, Holly. \"Meet J. Mark Spalding\", ''Tennessean'', February 1, 2018]</ref> among his relatives are [[Martin John Spalding]], [[John Lancaster Spalding]] and [[Catherine Spalding]]. He was graduated from [[Bethlehem High School (Bardstown, Kentucky)]] in 1983; and obtained a B.A. in history from [[Saint Meinrad Seminary and School of Theology]] in 1987. He received a master's degree from the [[KU Leuven|Catholic University of Louvain]] and an [[Bachelor of Sacred Theology|S.T.B.]] in 1990.<ref name=bpage>[https://dioceseofnashville.com/bishops-page \"Bishop's Page, Diocese of Nashville]</ref>\n\nHe was ordained to the Roman Catholic priesthood on August 3, 1991 for the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville]] at the [[Basilica of St. Joseph Proto-Cathedral]] by Archbishop [[Thomas C. Kelly]], and returned to Louvain for a [[Licentiate of Canon Law|Licentiate in Canon Law]].<ref name=bpage/>\n\nIn 2016, he was appointed pastor of Holy Name Catholic Church in Louisville.<ref>[http://www.oholyname.org/ \"History of Holy Name Catholic Church\"]</ref>\n\n===Bishop of Nashville===\n[[Pope Francis]] appointed Spalding on November 21, 2017 to be the twelfth bishop of the Diocese of Nashville.<ref name=RCDioceseNashville /><ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.usccb.org/news/2017/17-226.cfm | title=Pope Francis Names New Bishop of the Diocese of Nashville; Pope Francis also Names New Bishop of Jefferson City | date=November 21, 2017 | publisher=[[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] | accessdate=November 21, 2017 }}</ref> Spalding was consecrated and installed as bishop in a [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Mass]] on February 2, 2018;<ref name=RCDioceseNashville>{{cite web | url=http://www.dioceseofnashville.com/news/father-j-mark-spalding-appointed-12th-bishop-of-nashville-1 | title=Father J. Mark Spalding Appointed 12th Bishop of Nashville | last=Musacchio | first=Rick | date=November 21, 2017 | publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville]] | accessdate=November 21, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /> among the concelebrants of the Mass were Archbishop [[Christophe Pierre]] and Cardinal [[Justin Francis Rigali]].<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Catholicism|United States}} \n{{div col}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[Historical list of the Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[List of Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[Lists of patriarchs, archbishops, and bishops]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.dioceseofnashville.com/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville Official Site]\n*{{Vimeo|id=254025356|title=Ordination Mass}}\n\n==Episcopal succession==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box  \n\t|title=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Bishop of Nashville]]  \n\t|before= [[David Choby]]\n\t|after= Incumbent\n\t|years= 2018-Present | }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville|state=collapsed}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spalding, J. Mark}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lebanon, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:People from Washington County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n\n\n{{US-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Mark Spalding}}\n\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type              = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix  = [[Excellency|His Excellency]], [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name              = J. Mark Spalding\n| honorific-suffix  = [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]], [[Licentiate of Canon Law|J.C.L.]]\n| title             = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Bishop of Nashville]]\n| image             = J. Mark Spalding 2019.png\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Spalding in 2019\n| archdiocese       = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville|Louisville]]\n| diocese           = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Nashville]]\n| appointed         = November 21, 2017\n| enthroned         = February 2 ([[Candlemas]]), 2018\n| retired           =\n| predecessor       = [[David Choby]]\n| successor         = \n| other_post        = \n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination        = August 3, 1991\n| ordained_by       = [[Thomas C. Kelly]], [[Dominican Order|O.P]]\n| consecration      = February 2 (Candlemas), 2018\n| consecrated_by    = [[Joseph Edward Kurtz]], [[Charles C. Thompson]], and [[William Medley]]<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram>{{cite book | last= | first= | authorlink= | title=Mass of the Episcopal Ordination and Installation of His Excellency, The Most Reverend J. Mark Spalding, D.D., J.C.L. as the Twelfth Bishop of Nashville (program) | publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville]] | series= | volume= | edition= | date= | location= | pages=36 | language=English | url= | doi= | id= | isbn= | mr= | zbl= | jfm=}}</ref>\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name        =  Joseph Mark Spalding<!---------- Archbishop Kurtz mistakenly identified him as Joseph Mark Spalding in the Mass of his episcopal ordination and installment ---------->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1965|01|13}} \n| birth_place       = [[Lebanon, Kentucky]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| buried            = \n| nationality       = {{flag|USA|name=American}}\n| religion          = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence         = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| parents           = Joseph Lawrence and Mary Aileen (nee Thompson) Spalding<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n| spouse            = \n| occupation        = \n| profession        = \n| previous_post     = [[Vicar general|Vicar General]] of Louisville (2011-2018)<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><br />Pastor of Holy Trinity Church ([[Louisville, Kentucky]]; 2011-2018)<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><br />Pastor of Holy Name Church (2016-2018)<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n| alma_mater        = [[Saint Meinrad Seminary and School of Theology]]<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><br />\"Catholic University of Louvain\"<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /> (it is not clear whether this refers to [[KU Leuven]] or [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]])\n| motto             = GOD HAS LIFTED UP THE LOWLY (from [[Magnificat#Roman Catholic translation|Luke 1:52]])<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n| coat_of_arms      = Coat of arms of J. Mark Spalding.svg\n}}\n\n{{Infobox bishopstyles  \n| name=  J. Mark Spalding\n| dipstyle=  \n*[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n*[[The Most Reverend]]    \n| offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] \n| relstyle=[[Bishop]] \n| image = Coat of arms of J. Mark Spalding.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Mark Spalding''',<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/nash1.htm#61700 | title=Diocese of Nashville USA | website=GCatholic.org | accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]],<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /> [[Licentiate of Canon Law|J.C.L.]] (born January 13, 1965 in [[Lebanon, Kentucky]]) is an [[United States|American]] priest and [[bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He is the twelfth [[bishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Diocese of Nashville]].<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n\n==Biography==\nSpalding was born in Lebanon, Kentucky and grew up on the family farm in [[Washington County, Kentucky|Washington County]]. His family has roots in the earliest [[Bardstown, Kentucky#History|Catholic presence in the United States west of the Appalachian Mountains]];<ref>[https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/religion/2018/02/01/nashville-new-bishop-j-mark-spalding/1018787001/ Meyer, Holly. \"Meet J. Mark Spalding\", ''Tenneseean'', February 1, 2018]</ref> among his relatives are [[Martin John Spalding]], [[John Lancaster Spalding]] and [[Catherine Spalding]]. He was graduated from [[Bethlehem High School (Bardstown, Kentucky)]] in 1983; and obtained a B.A. in history from [[Saint Meinrad Seminary and School of Theology]] in 1987. He received a master's degree from the [[KU Leuven|Catholic University of Louvain]] and an [[Bachelor of Sacred Theology|S.T.B.]] in 1990.<ref name=bpage>[https://dioceseofnashville.com/bishops-page \"Bishop's Page, Diocese of Nashville]</ref>\n\nHe was ordained to the Roman Catholic priesthood on August 3, 1991 for the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville]] at the [[Basilica of St. Joseph Proto-Cathedral]] by Archbishop [[Thomas C. Kelly]], and returned to Louvain for a [[Licentiate of Canon Law|Licentiate in Canon Law]].<ref name=bpage/>\n\nIn 2016, he was appointed pastor of Holy Name Catholic Church in Louisville.<ref>[http://www.oholyname.org/ \"History of Holy Name Catholic Church\"]</ref>\n\n===Bishop of Nashville===\n[[Pope Francis]] appointed Spalding on November 21, 2017 to be the twelfth bishop of the Diocese of Nashville.<ref name=RCDioceseNashville /><ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.usccb.org/news/2017/17-226.cfm | title=Pope Francis Names New Bishop of the Diocese of Nashville; Pope Francis also Names New Bishop of Jefferson City | date=November 21, 2017 | publisher=[[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] | accessdate=November 21, 2017 }}</ref> Spalding was consecrated and installed as bishop in a [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Mass]] on February 2, 2018;<ref name=RCDioceseNashville>{{cite web | url=http://www.dioceseofnashville.com/news/father-j-mark-spalding-appointed-12th-bishop-of-nashville-1 | title=Father J. Mark Spalding Appointed 12th Bishop of Nashville | last=Musacchio | first=Rick | date=November 21, 2017 | publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville]] | accessdate=November 21, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=SpaldingMassprogram /> among the concelebrants of the Mass were Archbishop [[Christophe Pierre]] and Cardinal [[Justin Francis Rigali]].<ref name=SpaldingMassprogram />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Catholicism|United States}} \n{{div col}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[Historical list of the Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[List of Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[Lists of patriarchs, archbishops, and bishops]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.dioceseofnashville.com/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville Official Site]\n*{{Vimeo|id=254025356|title=Ordination Mass}}\n\n==Episcopal succession==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{succession box  \n\t|title=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|Bishop of Nashville]]  \n\t|before= [[David Choby]]\n\t|after= Incumbent\n\t|years= 2018-Present | }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville|state=collapsed}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spalding, J. Mark}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lebanon, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:People from Washington County, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Nashville]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Louisville]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n\n\n{{US-RC-bishop-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Typo fixing, replaced: Tenneseean \u2192 Tennessean", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._Mark_Spalding"}
{"title_page": "Ivakovo", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Ivakovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Nikolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|45|N|45|23|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/nikolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Ivakovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0418\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Terebayevskoye Rural Settlement, [[Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Nikolsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 6 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Nikolsk, Vologda Oblast|Nikolsk]] is 31&nbsp;km, to Terebayevo is 13&nbsp;km. Kalinino is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Ivakovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Nikolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|45|N|45|23|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/nikolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Ivakovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0418\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Terebayevskoye Rural Settlement, [[Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Nikolsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 6 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Nikolsk, Vologda Oblast|Nikolsk]] is 31&nbsp;km, to Terebayevo is 13&nbsp;km. Kalinino is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Nikolsky District, Vologda Oblast]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivakovo"}
{"title_page": "Quintus Smyrnaeus", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n'''Quintus Smyrnaeus''' or '''Quintus of Smyrna''', also known as   '''Kointos Smyrnaios''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03cc\u03ca\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03bc\u03c5\u03c1\u03bd\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2}}), was a [[Greece|Greek]] [[Epic poetry|epic]] [[poet]] whose ''[[Posthomerica]]'', following \"after Homer\" continues the narration of the [[Trojan War]]. He has traditionally been thought to have lived in the latter part of the 4th century AD, but early dates have also been proposed.\n\nHis epic in fourteen books, known as the ''Posthomerica'', covers the period between the end of [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]'' and the end of the [[Trojan War]].  Its primary importance is as the earliest surviving work to cover this period, the archaic works in the [[Epic Cycle]], which he knew and drew upon, having been lost. His materials are borrowed from the cyclic poems from which [[Virgil]] (with whose works he was probably acquainted) also drew, in particular the ''[[Aethiopis]]'' (''Coming of Memnon'') and the ''[[Iliupersis]]'' (''Destruction of Troy'') of [[Arctinus of Miletus]] and the ''[[Little Iliad|Ilias Mikra]]'' (''Little Iliad'') of [[Lesches]]. His work is closely modelled on Homer, though Quintus is universally acknowledged to be inferior to Homer as a poet.\n\n==Life==\nThe dates of Quintus's life are controversial,{{fact|date=January 2020}} but they are traditionally placed in the latter part of the 4th century AD. \"His date is approximately settled by two passages in the poem, viz. vi. 531 sqq., in which occurs an illustration drawn from the [[Gladiator|man-and-beast fights of the amphitheatre]], which were suppressed by [[Theodosius I]]. (379-395 A.D.); and xiii. 335 sqq., which contains a prophecy, the special particularity of which, it is maintained by Koechly, limits its applicability to the middle of the fourth century A.D.\"<ref>Way, [https://archive.org/stream/falloftroy00quin#page/n7/mode/2up pp. v&ndash;vi].</ref>\n\nSome scholars{{who|date=January 2020}} suggest an earlier date in the 3rd or even the 2nd century, arguing that his ''Posthomerica'' shows an influence from the \"[[Second Sophistic]]\", the school of Greek  orators who flourished in the 1st and 2nd centuries.{{fact|date=January 2020}} According to his own account (xii. 310), he began composing poetry in his early youth while tending sheep near Smyrna (present-day [[\u0130zmir]]).<ref>This may be read as a literary ''[[literary topos|topos]]'', aligning him with the herder-poet [[Hesiod]]. There are parallels in the early careers of [[Apollo]] and [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] as well.</ref>{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\nA [[Christians|Christian]] poet of the 4th-century, [[Dorotheus (poet)|Dorotheus]], known for his Greek epic poem, ''[[The Vision of Dorotheus]]'', has been identified as the son of Quintus Smyrnaeus. At the end of the manuscript of his ''Vision'', he identifies himself as \"Dorotheus, son of Quintus the poet\". This identification is supported by the facts that there is no other poet Quintus in this period and Dorotheus uses the same Homeric poetic structure as Quintus. Despite this, Dorotheus commits many metric errors which Quintus avoids, indicating that Dorotheus did not inherit Quintus' homeric culture.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bremmer |first=Jan N. |date=2002 |chapter=God\u2019s heavenly palace as a military court: ''The Vision of Dorotheus'' |title=The Rise and Fall of the Afterlife. The 1995 Read-Tuckwell Lecture at the University of Bristol |pages=[https://archive.org/details/risefallofafterl0000brem/page/128 128-133] |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9780415141482 |url=https://archive.org/details/risefallofafterl0000brem/page/128 }}\n</ref>\n\n==The ''Posthomerica''==\n{{main|Posthomerica}}\n[[File:Posthomerica.tif|thumb|''Posthomerica'', 1541]]\n\nThe first four books, covering the same ground as the ''[[Aethiopis]]'' of [[Arctinus of Miletus]], describe the doughty deeds and deaths of the [[Amazons|Amazon]] [[Penthesileia]] and of [[Memnon (mythology)|Memnon]] the son of the dawn goddess[[Eos]], both slain by Achilles, and the death of [[Achilles]] himself and the funeral games in his honour. \n\nBooks five through twelve, covering the same ground as the ''[[Little Iliad]]'' of [[Lesches]], span the contest between [[Telamonian Ajax|Aias]] and [[Odysseus]] for the arms of Achilles, the death of Aias of suicide after his loss, the exploits of [[Neoptolemus]], [[Eurypylus (son of Telephus)|Eurypylus]] and [[Deiphobus]], the deaths of [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] and [[Oenone]], and the building of the [[Trojan Horse|wooden horse]]. \n\nThe remaining books, covering the same ground as [[Arctinus]]' ''[[The Sack of Troy]]'', relate the capture of Troy by means of the wooden horse, the sacrifice of [[Polyxena]] at the grave of Achilles, the departure of the Greeks, and their dispersal by storm.\n\n==Editions==\nThe ''[[Editio princeps]]'' by [[Aldus Manutius]] was published at Venice, 1504 under the title ''Quinti Calabri derelictorum ab Homero libri XIV''.  Aldus calls him '''Quintus Calaber''', because the only known manuscript of his poem was discovered at [[Otranto]] in [[Calabria]] by [[Johannes Bessarion|Cardinal Bessarion]], in 1450. His familiar name was first given him by his editor Lorenz Rhodomann, in 1577, who included a Latin translation by [[Michael Neander]].<ref>''Cointi Smyrnaei, popularis Homeri, po\u00ebtae vetustissimi et suavissimi, Ilii excidii libri duo, Reditus Graecorum capta liber unus. Expositi olim in schola Ilfeldensi et editi nunc studio, industria et labore Laurentii Rhodomanni.'' (Leipzig: Steinmann) 1577.</ref>\n\nThere has been a renewed interest in the poet and his poem in the twentieth century, with A. Way's translation (Loeb Classical Library vol. 19, 1913); a new edition of the text with partial commentary and French translation done by [[Francis Vian]] (3 vols. published by Bud\u00e9, 1963, 1966, 1969); [[Frederick Combellack]]'s  English translation (1968); Alan James and Kevin Lee's detailed commentary on book 5; and Alan James's English translation, with newly edited text and commentary (''Quintus of Smyrna. The Trojan Epic. Posthomerica.''   Baltimore and London:  Johns Hopkins University Press, 2004).\n\n==Notes==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* Way, A. S., ''Quintus Smyrnaeus: The Fall of Troy'', Translator: A.S. Way; Harvard University Press, Cambridge Massachusetts, 1913. [https://archive.org/stream/falloftroy00quin#page/n5/mode/2up Internet Archive]\n\n<!--The following are outdated and unavailable:*[[Hermann Kochly]] (ed. major with elaborate prolegomena, 1850; ed. minor, 1853)\n*[[Z. Zimmermann]] (author of other valuable articles on the poet), (1891)\n*[[Franz Kehmptzow]], ''De Quinti Smyrnaei fontibus ac mythopoeia'' (1889)\n*[[Charles Augustin Sainte-Beuve|C.-A. Sainte-Beuve]], ''Etude sur .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Quinte de Smyrne'' (1857)\n*[[Frederick Apthorp Paley|F.A. Paley]], ''Quintus Smyrnaeus and the \"Homer\" of the tragic Poets'' (1879)\n*[[G. W. Paschal]], ''A Study of Quintus Smyrnaeus'' (Chicago, 1904).-->\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Quintus Smyrnaeus|volume=22}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Quintus,+Smyrnaeus | name=Smyrnaeus Quintus}} {{dead link|date=July 2015}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Quintus Smyrnaeus}}\n* [http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb10169448_00001.html Editio princeps (Greek text, Venice, Aldus)]\n* [http://www.gltc.leidenuniv.nl/index.php3?c=154 Quintus Smyrnaeus: a modern bibliography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quintus Smyrnaeus}}\n[[Category:Roman-era poets]]\n[[Category:Late Antique writers]]\n[[Category:Roman-era Greeks]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek epic poets]]\n[[Category:4th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Ancient Smyrnaeans]]\n[[Category:People from \u0130zmir]]\n[[Category:Poets of ancient Ionia]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}\n'''Quintus Smyrnaeus''' or '''Quintus of Smyrna''', also known as   '''Kointos Smyrnaios''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03cc\u03ca\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a3\u03bc\u03c5\u03c1\u03bd\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2}}), was a [[Greece|Greek]] [[Epic poetry|epic]] [[poet]] whose ''[[Posthomerica]]'', following \"after Homer\" continues the narration of the [[Trojan War]]. He has traditionally been thought to have lived in the latter part of the 4th century AD, but early dates have also been proposed.\n\nHis epic in fourteen books, known as the ''Posthomerica'', covers the period between the end of [[Homer]]'s ''[[Iliad]]'' and the end of the [[Trojan War]].  Its primary importance is as the earliest surviving work to cover this period, the archaic works in the [[Epic Cycle]], which he knew and drew upon, having been lost. His materials are borrowed from the cyclic poems from which [[Virgil]] (with whose works he was probably acquainted) also drew, in particular the ''[[Aethiopis]]'' (''Coming of Memnon'') and the ''[[Iliupersis]]'' (''Destruction of Troy'') of [[Arctinus of Miletus]] and the ''[[Little Iliad|Ilias Mikra]]'' (''Little Iliad'') of [[Lesches]]. His work is closely modelled on Homer, though Quintus is universally acknowledged to be inferior to Homer as a poet.\n\n==Life==\nThe dates of Quintus's life are controversial,{{fact|date=January 2020}} but they are traditionally placed in the latter part of the 4th century AD. \"His date is approximately settled by two passages in the poem, viz. vi. 531 sqq., in which occurs an illustration drawn from the [[Gladiator|man-and-beast fights of the amphitheatre]], which were suppressed by [[Theodosius I]]. (379-395 A.D.); and xiii. 335 sqq., which contains a prophecy, the special particularity of which, it is maintained by Koechly, limits its applicability to the middle of the fourth century A.D.\"<ref>Way, [https://archive.org/stream/falloftroy00quin#page/n7/mode/2up pp. v&ndash;vi].</ref>\n\nSome scholars{{who|date=January 2020}} suggest an earlier date in the 3rd or even the 2nd century, arguing that his ''Posthomerica'' shows an influence from the \"[[Second Sophistic]]\", the school of Greek  orators who flourished in the 1st and 2nd centuries.{{fact|date=January 2020}} According to his own account (xii. 310), he began composing poetry in his early youth while tending sheep near Smyrna (present-day [[\u0130zmir]]).<ref>This may be read as a literary ''[[literary topos|topos]]'', aligning him with the herder-poet [[Hesiod]]. There are parallels in the early careers of [[Apollo]] and [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] as well.</ref>{{fact|date=January 2020}}\n\nA [[Christian]] poet of the 4th-century, [[Dorotheus (poet)|Dorotheus]], known for his Greek epic poem, ''[[The Vision of Dorotheus]]'', has been identified as the son of Quintus Smyrnaeus. At the end of the manuscript of his ''Vision'', he identifies himself as \"Dorotheus, son of Quintus the poet\". This identification is supported by the facts that there is no other poet Quintus in this period and Dorotheus uses the same Homeric poetic structure as Quintus. Despite this, Dorotheus commits many metric errors which Quintus avoids, indicating that Dorotheus did not inherit Quintus' homeric culture.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bremmer |first=Jan N. |date=2002 |chapter=God\u2019s heavenly palace as a military court: ''The Vision of Dorotheus'' |title=The Rise and Fall of the Afterlife. The 1995 Read-Tuckwell Lecture at the University of Bristol |pages=[https://archive.org/details/risefallofafterl0000brem/page/128 128-133] |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9780415141482 |url=https://archive.org/details/risefallofafterl0000brem/page/128 }}\n</ref>\n\n==The ''Posthomerica''==\n{{main|Posthomerica}}\n[[File:Posthomerica.tif|thumb|''Posthomerica'', 1541]]\n\nThe first four books, covering the same ground as the ''[[Aethiopis]]'' of [[Arctinus of Miletus]], describe the doughty deeds and deaths of the [[Amazons|Amazon]] [[Penthesileia]] and of [[Memnon (mythology)|Memnon]] the son of the dawn goddess[[Eos]], both slain by Achilles, and the death of [[Achilles]] himself and the funeral games in his honour. \n\nBooks five through twelve, covering the same ground as the ''[[Little Iliad]]'' of [[Lesches]], span the contest between [[Telamonian Ajax|Aias]] and [[Odysseus]] for the arms of Achilles, the death of Aias of suicide after his loss, the exploits of [[Neoptolemus]], [[Eurypylus (son of Telephus)|Eurypylus]] and [[Deiphobus]], the deaths of [[Paris (mythology)|Paris]] and [[Oenone]], and the building of the [[Trojan Horse|wooden horse]]. \n\nThe remaining books, covering the same ground as [[Arctinus]]' ''[[The Sack of Troy]]'', relate the capture of Troy by means of the wooden horse, the sacrifice of [[Polyxena]] at the grave of Achilles, the departure of the Greeks, and their dispersal by storm.\n\n==Editions==\nThe ''[[Editio princeps]]'' by [[Aldus Manutius]] was published at Venice, 1504 under the title ''Quinti Calabri derelictorum ab Homero libri XIV''.  Aldus calls him '''Quintus Calaber''', because the only known manuscript of his poem was discovered at [[Otranto]] in [[Calabria]] by [[Johannes Bessarion|Cardinal Bessarion]], in 1450. His familiar name was first given him by his editor Lorenz Rhodomann, in 1577, who included a Latin translation by [[Michael Neander]].<ref>''Cointi Smyrnaei, popularis Homeri, po\u00ebtae vetustissimi et suavissimi, Ilii excidii libri duo, Reditus Graecorum capta liber unus. Expositi olim in schola Ilfeldensi et editi nunc studio, industria et labore Laurentii Rhodomanni.'' (Leipzig: Steinmann) 1577.</ref>\n\nThere has been a renewed interest in the poet and his poem in the twentieth century, with A. Way's translation (Loeb Classical Library vol. 19, 1913); a new edition of the text with partial commentary and French translation done by [[Francis Vian]] (3 vols. published by Bud\u00e9, 1963, 1966, 1969); [[Frederick Combellack]]'s  English translation (1968); Alan James and Kevin Lee's detailed commentary on book 5; and Alan James's English translation, with newly edited text and commentary (''Quintus of Smyrna. The Trojan Epic. Posthomerica.''   Baltimore and London:  Johns Hopkins University Press, 2004).\n\n==Notes==\n<!--This article uses the Cite.php citation mechanism. If you would like more information on how to add references to this article, please see http://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/Cite/Cite.php -->\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* Way, A. S., ''Quintus Smyrnaeus: The Fall of Troy'', Translator: A.S. Way; Harvard University Press, Cambridge Massachusetts, 1913. [https://archive.org/stream/falloftroy00quin#page/n5/mode/2up Internet Archive]\n\n<!--The following are outdated and unavailable:*[[Hermann Kochly]] (ed. major with elaborate prolegomena, 1850; ed. minor, 1853)\n*[[Z. Zimmermann]] (author of other valuable articles on the poet), (1891)\n*[[Franz Kehmptzow]], ''De Quinti Smyrnaei fontibus ac mythopoeia'' (1889)\n*[[Charles Augustin Sainte-Beuve|C.-A. Sainte-Beuve]], ''Etude sur .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Quinte de Smyrne'' (1857)\n*[[Frederick Apthorp Paley|F.A. Paley]], ''Quintus Smyrnaeus and the \"Homer\" of the tragic Poets'' (1879)\n*[[G. W. Paschal]], ''A Study of Quintus Smyrnaeus'' (Chicago, 1904).-->\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Quintus Smyrnaeus|volume=22}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Quintus,+Smyrnaeus | name=Smyrnaeus Quintus}} {{dead link|date=July 2015}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Quintus Smyrnaeus}}\n* [http://reader.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb10169448_00001.html Editio princeps (Greek text, Venice, Aldus)]\n* [http://www.gltc.leidenuniv.nl/index.php3?c=154 Quintus Smyrnaeus: a modern bibliography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Quintus Smyrnaeus}}